  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Sailing to Laizhou Sea
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Ten-fathom masts on a ship that holds ten thousand measures—
    Clouds part to reveal the vast azure sea without horizon.
    Stars hang low, mirroring the snow-white waves,
    Water crashes against the Milky Way, their banks converging.

    Midway across the ocean, one might grieve for fallen warriors,
    Yet why seek immortals on distant fairy isles?
    Reclining in the cabin, riding the wave of delight,
    This humble vessel seems to drift upward toward heaven itself.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Milky Way' (銀河) creates a poetic collapse between earthly sea and celestial river, a common device in Chinese poetry suggesting the transcendence of ordinary bounds.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'three islands' (三島) alludes to legendary islands of immortals in East Asian mythology, which the poet dismisses in favor of finding wonder in the present moment.
  - key: ''
    value: The floating raft imagery evokes the legend of a man who rode a raft to heaven, suggesting spiritual ascension through natural transport rather than supernatural seeking.
